   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0179.xml"/>Ebenezer
            Blackwell</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>Bandon</placeName><lb/><date when="1758-07-12">July 12, 1758</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute/>
         </opener>
         <p>Really, sir, you had made me almost angry at an innocent person— I mean, innocent of the
            fault supposed. I wrote to Mr. <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0611.xml"
               />Downing</persName><note place="foot" n="1"><persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0611.xml"/>George Downing</persName> (c. <date from="1729"
                  to="1809">1729–1809</date>) was a priest in the Church of
                  <placeName>England</placeName> sympathetic with the Evangelical revival, at least
               with its &apos;regular&apos; wing who stressed conformity to church law. He was
               rector of <placeName>Ovington, Essex</placeName>, and also served as chaplain to
                  <persName>William Legge</persName><!-- No specific persID yet -->, the second Earl
               of Dartmouth.</note> nearly at the time I wrote to you; and seeing no name, I read
            part of your letter as from <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0611.xml"
               />him</persName>, and thought &apos;My <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"
               />wife</persName> did very wrong to trouble <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0611.xml"/>him</persName> with matters of this kind, which
            might do <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0611.xml"/>him</persName> more harm than
            good&apos;. Time and patience will remove many other troubles, and show them to have no
            more foundation than this.</p>
         <p>While you have so eloquent a person<note place="foot" n="2">Apparently referring to
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>Mary Wesley</persName>.</note>
            at your elbow, and I am two or three hundred miles off, I have little to say. It may be
            time enough when I return to <placeName>London</placeName>. At present I would only make
            two or three cursory remarks.</p>
         <p>1) That letter was not <hi rend="italic">left on a chair</hi>, but <hi rend="italic"
               >taken out of my</hi> pocket.<note place="foot" n="3">See <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s letter to <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers1793.xml"/>Sarah Ryan</persName>, <date when="1756-01-27"
                  >Jan. 27,
               1756</date>.<!-- I personally believe this should be the letter of Jan. 27, 1758 not 56 --></note></p>
         <p>2) It was not <hi rend="italic">letters</hi>, but a <hi rend="italic">letter</hi> of
            mine (and one which did not signify a straw) which <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0506.xml"/>Sarah Crosby</persName> some time since showed to
            three or four persons, and of which she will hear these ten years.<note place="foot"
               n="4">&apos;years&apos; is clear in the manuscript, but <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> perhaps meant to write
               &apos;weeks&apos;.</note> I write to <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0506.xml"
               />her</persName> when I judge it my duty so to do; but I have not wrote these ten or
            twelve weeks.</p>
         <p>3) If you softened or salved over anything I wrote in the letter from Bedford,<note
               place="foot" n="5"><persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> was
               in <placeName>Bedford</placeName>
               <date from="1758-03-09" to="1758-03-10">Mar. 9–10</date>; no letter to his
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>wife</persName> of this date has
               survived.</note> you did <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"
               />her</persName> an irreparable damage. What <hi rend="italic">I</hi> am is not the
            question there, but what <hi rend="italic"><persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"
                  />she</persName></hi> is, of which I must needs be a better judge than you, for I
            wear the shoe—as you must needs be a better judge of Mrs. <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0180.xml"/>[Elizabeth] Blackwell</persName>&apos;s temper
            than I.</p>
         <p>4) &apos;<persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>She</persName> is now full of
            anger.&apos; High day! Anger! For what? Why because when <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0527.xml"/>Captain Dansey</persName> called upon me in
               <placeName>Dublin</placeName> (on the <date when="1758-04-07">7th of April</date>)
            and asked, &apos;Sir, have you any commands? I am just sailing for
               <placeName>Bristol</placeName>&apos;, I said, &apos;Yes. Here is a letter. Will you
            deliver it with your own hands?&apos;<note place="foot" n="6">No letter from
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> to his
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>wife</persName> has survived
               from this period either.</note>
            <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0527.xml"/>He</persName> promised <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0527.xml"/>he</persName> would, and that was our whole
            conversation.</p>
         <p>5) But suppose <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0527.xml"/>he</persName> delivered
            this about the <date when="1758-04-12">12th of April</date>, why did <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>she</persName> not write for a month before? What
            excuse or pretence for this?</p>
         <p>6) I certainly will, as long as I can hold a pen, assert my right of conversing with
            whom I please. Reconciliation or none, let <hi rend="italic"><persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>her</persName></hi> look to that. If the
            unbeliever will depart, let <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2091.xml"
               />her</persName> depart. That right I will exert just when I judge proper, giving an
            account only to God and my own conscience. Though (as it happens) the last letter I
            wrote to <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1793.xml"/>Sarah Ryan</persName> was in the
            beginning of <date when="1758-05">May</date>.<note place="foot" n="7">This letter has
               not survived.</note></p>
         <p>7) My conscience bears me witness before God that I have been as &apos;cautious as I
            ought to have been&apos;; for I have rigorously kept my rule, &apos;To <hi rend="italic"
               >do</hi> everything and <hi rend="italic">omit</hi> everything which I could with a
            safe conscience for peace sake&apos;.</p>
         <p>But there is no fence against a flail, against one that could tell <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers2127.xml"/>Thomas Walsh</persName> calmly and deliberately
                  (<persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2127.xml"/>he</persName> begs this may not be
            mentioned again, nor <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2127.xml"/>his</persName> name
            brought into the question), &apos;His parting words to me were, &quot;I hope I shall see
            your wicked face no more.&apos; &quot; Can you ever be safe against being deceived by
            such an one but by not believing a word you hear?</p>
         <p>In a week or two I shall be looking out for a ship. You people in
               <placeName>England</placeName> are bad correspondents. Both <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0611.xml"/>Mr. Downing</persName>, <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers2093.xml"/>Mr. Venn</persName>,<note place="foot" n="8">On
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2093.xml"/>Henry Venn</persName> (<date
                  from="1725" to="1797">1725–97</date>), see 26:535 in this edn.</note> and
                  <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1341.xml"/>Mr. Madan</persName><note
               place="foot" n="9"><persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1341.xml"/>Martin
                  Madan</persName> (<date from="1725" to="1790">1725–90</date>) was a
               &apos;spiritual son&apos; of <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />JW</persName>, awakened under <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />his</persName> preaching. But <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1341.xml"
                  />Madan</persName> soon aligned with more Calvinist-leaning evangelicals like
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0964.xml"/>Lady Huntingdon</persName>,
                  <persName>David Jones</persName>, <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1771.xml"
                  />William Romaine</persName>, and <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2221.xml"
                  />George Whitefield</persName>.</note> are a letter in my debt; and yet I think
            they have not more business than I have. How unequally are things distributed here! Some
            want time, and some want work! But all will be set right hereafter. There is no disorder
            on that shore.</p>
         <closer>Wishing all happiness to you and all that are with you, I remain,
            dear sir,<lb/>
            <signed>Yours most affectionately,<lb/><persName>J.W.</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
</TEI>
